{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"39fe81b0-1dd4-4c7a-83e2-a37f5295e68e","content":"The best approach is `dotnet-trace` with the CPU profiling profile:\n\n```bash\n# Install the tool (if not already in the container)\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace\n\n# Find your app's PID\ndotnet-trace ps\n\n# Collect a 30-second CPU trace\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\nThis produces a `.nettrace` file you can analyze in **Visual Studio**, **PerfView**, or convert to speedscope format:\n\n```bash\ndotnet-trace convert trace.nettrace --format Speedscope\n```\n\n**Tips:**\n- If you can't install tools in the container, use a [sidecar or ephemeral debug container](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/core/diagnostics/dotnet-trace#collect-using-an-ephemeral-container).\n- For production, consider `--buffersize 256` to reduce overhead.\n- Alternative: `dotnet-counters monitor -p <PID>` for a quick live view before committing to a full trace.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"65d168e5-389c-4127-ae53-621ac72ce102","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a CPU trace from a .NET 8 app running in a Kubernetes pod on Linux. This is a knowledge/advice question, not a code change task. I'll provide a concise answer.","outputTokens":333,"requestId":"C3C6:27C37:1DD701D:217A183:6A07C38D"},"id":"a91baf0a-f859-4f39-92be-2e9941121e4e","timestamp":"2026-05-16T01:08:37.993Z","parentId":"0a8c9261-1c52-4dd3-b8a2-55a62850ccee"}
